WEBVTT

00:00:02.880 --> 00:00:09.080
Everybody here at the Denver airport and I'm going to keep it short so I don't annoy my

00:00:09.740 --> 00:00:11.000
fellow guest here.

00:00:13.740 --> 00:00:21.140
But the one thing I started playing with was seeing how small I could get an LLM.

00:00:22.160 --> 00:00:26.380
And as a joke, I did a post on Reddit about a one-parameter LLM.

00:00:27.160 --> 00:00:31.200
And all it would do is look and see if you said Scarlett or Johansson.

00:00:31.720 --> 00:00:37.960
And then it would just gush about Scarlett Johansson, her voice, her Oscar, were the

00:00:37.960 --> 00:00:41.720
performance and how no way I could ever recreate that beautiful voice of hers.

00:00:42.460 --> 00:00:43.660
So kind of a dig at Steve Altman.

00:00:45.660 --> 00:00:50.860
It turned out there is such a thing as a one-parameter model and there's such a thing as a zero-parameter

00:00:50.860 --> 00:00:52.560
model, which seemed crazy.

00:00:52.560 --> 00:01:01.680
So a zero-parameter model is a model that is just an echo model.

00:01:02.440 --> 00:01:05.000
Like let's say you send it true, it returns true.

00:01:05.920 --> 00:01:07.440
If you send it false, it returns false.

00:01:07.600 --> 00:01:09.300
Just returns whatever token you send it.

00:01:09.520 --> 00:01:10.620
And it can only take one token.

00:01:13.760 --> 00:01:20.380
But it does have a logical purpose, which determines whether statements are true or

00:01:20.380 --> 00:01:20.660
false.

00:01:20.660 --> 00:01:25.760
If you can condense your statement on an earlier stage of the pipeline to true or false and

00:01:25.760 --> 00:01:28.060
you feed it to this, it'll let you know if it's true or false.

00:01:28.340 --> 00:01:29.740
And you could do that as an output token.

00:01:30.680 --> 00:01:31.460
So it's kind of strange.

00:01:33.020 --> 00:01:40.880
So then I was like, OK, I've done zero, I've done one, the two smallest models in the world

00:01:40.880 --> 00:01:42.560
really fast, by the way.

00:01:43.280 --> 00:01:48.920
And then I moved from then I moved to like 10x every time.

00:01:49.440 --> 00:01:53.420
So instead of like doubling, I'm doing 10x the size of the model every time.

00:01:54.180 --> 00:01:56.880
And right now I'm at 500 million parameters.

00:01:58.620 --> 00:02:03.660
I was certain in the early stages, I said, let's teach it math.

00:02:04.660 --> 00:02:05.420
Let's teach it logic.

00:02:05.520 --> 00:02:08.260
I taught it logic first, like Boolean logic.

00:02:08.540 --> 00:02:09.320
And I taught it math.

00:02:10.020 --> 00:02:13.000
I taught the Socratic dialogues, you know, Plato.

00:02:14.360 --> 00:02:17.860
I kind of followed the Western canon because that's what I understand.

00:02:17.860 --> 00:02:25.220
After it got good at proving things to give it a moral compass, I did the new testament.

00:02:26.020 --> 00:02:35.880
I did without all the genealogy stuff, which I'm not a theologist, but I don't see the

00:02:35.880 --> 00:02:38.720
purpose of training a model to do all that.

00:02:39.940 --> 00:02:46.040
And a really interesting thing is that earlier versions of the model, they're all mathematically

00:02:46.040 --> 00:02:46.640
provable.

00:02:46.640 --> 00:02:51.640
And I've created some proofs, actually went on fire and hired a very nice mathematician, a

00:02:51.640 --> 00:02:57.100
Muslim mathematician from Pakistan who verified everything was mathematically correct.

00:02:58.860 --> 00:03:04.080
Once you incorporate like the entire English language, there's a lot of stuff that like if I

00:03:04.080 --> 00:03:07.560
say Adam is a jerk, how do you prove that when we're allowed?

00:03:07.960 --> 00:03:14.220
So I divided English into English that can be proven and English that can't be proven.

00:03:14.220 --> 00:03:17.860
So Adam is six foot 10 that that can be proven.

00:03:18.200 --> 00:03:19.600
Adam is a jerk, cannot be proven.

00:03:21.260 --> 00:03:23.260
And so that's where I am.

00:03:24.500 --> 00:03:26.860
It's really a pretty useful model already.

00:03:27.220 --> 00:03:32.880
And the smaller models are super useful at doing things like playing chess or at doing

00:03:32.880 --> 00:03:40.220
things like investigating whether you have network intrusion in real time because they're

00:03:40.220 --> 00:03:40.780
so fast.

00:03:40.780 --> 00:03:50.600
And by fast, I mean that my model to detect network intrusion operates in 14 microseconds and

00:03:50.600 --> 00:03:57.220
llama eight billion, pretty small model, llama eight billion takes about 253 milliseconds, and

00:03:57.220 --> 00:03:58.340
they get similar results.

00:03:58.620 --> 00:04:01.800
And I would argue that mine are more logically accurate.

00:04:02.920 --> 00:04:08.700
Like they have my models have perfect accuracy, but the time and only useful for very

00:04:09.580 --> 00:04:11.420
mathy logic, you sort of things.

00:04:14.760 --> 00:04:16.420
So where do we go from here?

00:04:16.640 --> 00:04:18.640
I mean, I have the 500 billion parameter model.

00:04:19.380 --> 00:04:26.980
I started having it look at all the logic in the Bible and to say, hey, is Jesus argument

00:04:26.980 --> 00:04:31.940
about if you're a Christian, you'll know the argument about render and disease.

00:04:32.240 --> 00:04:38.220
So it analyzes that argument says that Jesus actually got it right that they're trying to

00:04:38.220 --> 00:04:39.660
get them on the horns of the dilemma.

00:04:40.100 --> 00:04:43.420
But it turned out that they were framing the question improperly.

00:04:43.760 --> 00:04:45.060
And that's what he called them out on.

00:04:46.380 --> 00:04:47.620
So kind of interesting stuff.

00:04:48.060 --> 00:04:54.280
And if you're not Christian, if that first statement, true equals true requires faith, you

00:04:54.280 --> 00:04:56.880
have to admit that there is such a thing as truth.

00:04:57.660 --> 00:05:03.080
If you say no, everything's relative and it's different for Christian, the Muslim, the Hindu,

00:05:03.260 --> 00:05:06.700
the Buddhist, they all have different versions of truth and there's no trick or true.

00:05:07.420 --> 00:05:10.700
And this logic is not going to make any sense to you.

00:05:10.840 --> 00:05:12.980
And there are parts of the world that it doesn't make any sense.

00:05:13.140 --> 00:05:15.660
This is a very Western scientific method thing.

00:05:16.280 --> 00:05:21.460
But if you say God is the truth and the light and whatever Jesus.

00:05:23.940 --> 00:05:27.860
And you say that faith, the true equals true, there is such a thing as truth and right and

00:05:27.860 --> 00:05:33.500
wrong, then that can be your how this logic starts.

00:05:34.140 --> 00:05:37.280
And let's say you're an atheist and say, I don't believe in that stuff.

00:05:37.400 --> 00:05:38.580
I do believe there is truth.

00:05:38.920 --> 00:05:40.980
I mean, I can mathematically prove something true.

00:05:41.800 --> 00:05:44.780
You can just substitute God in the first step with the scientific method.

00:05:45.520 --> 00:05:46.680
Makes no difference.

00:05:47.300 --> 00:05:51.560
The logic is sound regardless of where the.

00:05:52.520 --> 00:05:56.860
That's the first axiom and you got to start somewhere.

00:05:57.580 --> 00:05:59.740
So that first axiom is true equals true.

00:05:59.740 --> 00:06:02.960
And either that's true or it's not.

00:06:03.660 --> 00:06:05.580
So anyway, thank you for this short thing.

00:06:05.720 --> 00:06:10.860
I'll try to blur out all the people that didn't ask to be on my podcast and I will talk to you

